Activity Description: SARR Freedom Day 4 miler
Louisiana Marathon

Activity Name: Run for the hill of it

Activity Description: 1 mile warmup, 30 min tempo
1st in age group
Accidentally paused my watch during one repeat...
Expected it to be tough with the hills and rain. Wasn’t expecting the extra half mile. 1st Master/4th overall
Finally dry enough to get back on the trails
Faster than I expected. Top of age group, and ready for rock and roll next month
7x800.  I missed the button on the watch and didn't record the first one.
Took it easy for 10, then ran the downhill last 3 hard. 2 minute PR on a hilly course, so now looking to go sub 1:35 at Rock and Roll.

Activity Name: Rock and Roll San Antonio Half

Activity Description: Didn’t hit goal pace for the two miles that were into the crazy headwind. Overall tougher effort than I was expecting.
Felt good through 17 then had to push to hold pace for the last 5.
6:59, 7:06, 7:07, 7:20, 7:11. Just off 7 min goal pace, but about what I expected on tired legs.
First 10 with SARR then on my own for the second half. Progressively faster the whole way and felt strong at the end which was encouraging after having some disappointing efforts this week.
Tried to sneak this in today but ended up cutting it in half.  Between a full stomach and the wind I just wasn’t feeling it.
Back and forth between paved paths and trails so the splits are all over the place.  Didn't really feel like doing this today and almost quit 4 or 5 times, but got through it.
Last long run before Houston!  Definitely looking forward to tapering after 4 straight weeks around 50 miles.

Activity Name: 6 easy, 9x 400 (2 min jog), 1 mile cool down
Activity Description: 90 sec goal for the intervals. A couple 92s with the rest all at 90 or under.

Goal was marathon pace, but with traffic and intersections downtown it took a while to settle into a groove. Legs felt good and it definitely seemed like a pace I’ll be able to hold for the full next week.

Felt really strong and had to keep my pace in check for the first 18 or so. Tried to turn it up at mile 20 to shoot for 3:20 but my legs weren’t responding. The last two miles were tough, but overall I’m really pleased with the result.

Not sure why I wanted to do a half 2 weeks after a full. Tried to go out at PR pace but quickly realized my legs were heavy and that wasn’t going to work. Hung in for a decent time but the last 4 miles or so were pretty tough. 5th overall, 2nd Master, top of age group.

Activity Name: 20 min warm up, 3x 1 mile w/ 3 minute rest. 1 mile cool down
Activity Description: Not good. Was going to be 6x 1 mile but had no motivation or energy. 6:45 was the target pace but struggled to keep them under 7:00.  Ugh.

Activity Name: 20 min warm up, 8x1k + 3x200 (200m jog recoveries), 2 miles cool down

Activity Description: I was right on pace for 20 minutes which was great considering the tight course with sharp turns and pedestrians, too bad the course was short. I’ll try again for sub 20 next month but overall pretty happy with the effort and the win!
20 minute warm up, 2 miles @ 10k pace, 5 minute jog, 4x1 mile @ 10k pace with 3:00 jog recoveries. 6:40 target pace for the fast miles, and hit them all but the last one which was into the wind.

Activity Name: 20 min warm up, 5x200 + 4x100, 20 min cool down
Activity Description: 400 jog recovery on the 200s, 100 jog on the 100s. Really windy so the splits were all over, but the effort felt pretty good.

Activity Name: 20 min warm up, 20 min tempo, 20 min cool down
Activity Description: 7:00 min/mile goal pace.
Felt great for the first two miles, then hit the twisty parts and my hips weren’t having it. Really tough effort from there but managed to keep the pace pretty even and get 8th overall
20 min warmup. Was supposed to be 8 reps but I was gassed after 4.
20 minute warmup, 2 and 3 mile tempos with 1 mile jog between. 7:15 target pace and felt comfortable most of the way.
Decent pace to start but didn’t have anything extra for the second half. The race was a little short, so still looking for a legit sub 20.   4th overall
15 minute warm up, 400s @10k pace w/400 jog recoveries, 200s w/200 jog recoveries, 15 minute cool down.
15 minute warm up, 3 @ HM pace, cool down to 7 miles. 7:05 target and had to really push for 7:07, 7:03, 7:02. I’m definitely not in 1:30 Half marathon shape anymore...
15 minute warm up, 8x400 (400 jog), 6x200 (100 jog). After fueling with coffee and pizza rolls I knew this wasn’t going to be fast so I ignored the target paces and made it more of a fartlek.
15 minute warm up, 4 miles at HM pace, cool down to 8 miles. 7:05 goal pace and after the first mile it felt pretty comfortable. Lots of tents in the park already.
2nd overall.
Cool down to get to 8 miles for the day
With a big increase in mileage this week I didn’t have much in the tank for this one, and knowing the course would be short it wasn’t worth pushing too hard.
1st place in the military division.
If anyone is looking to run the trails at McAllister Park I just cleared out all the spiderwebs for you. I think it cost me at least 5 seconds per mile.
3 out, 3x up and down a little hill, 3 miles back. Not a full workout but it’s the first attempt since I started ramping up the mileage.

15 minute warmup, 8x400 with 400 jog, half mile easy, then 6x200 with 100 jog. First legit workout in quite a while and it showed.  I had nothing left by the time I got to the 200s. Felt good being back on the track though!
3rd overall and very happy with the time considering I was coming into it with tired legs.
Thought about going shorter today but it was a little cooler so went ahead and got this one over with. That humidity was brutal though.
Recovery run got a little more exciting when I ran into a bike race. The last couple miles had some dives into the bushes to avoid head on collisions. 3 out of the last 4 weeks over 50 miles.
2 mile warmup, 3 x 1 mile with .25 mile rest.  I was aiming for under 7 on the repeats, went 7:05/7:03/7:07, which is ok on tired legs.
2 mile warmup, 5x 3 minutes at Half Marathon pace with 2 minute jog.

Happy with the time overall but I could have raced a little better. Slowed down a lot in the second mile, and wasn’t able to kick through the last half mile as much as I wanted. 2nd in my age group, and much faster than last year!
4x up the hills with ~1.5 mile cool down
1 mile up/down. 2x 3 miles @ 7:30 per mile with 2 mile jog between.
2 miles up/down. 10x 400m with 1 min rest. Goal was 88 sec and was within 1 or 2 seconds for all of them
5 with SARR, then 6 at goal marathon pace and a one mile cool down. The fast portion didn’t feel too difficult, but I had trouble finding and maintaining a steady pace.

3 miles up, 8x600 with 400 recovery.  Goal was 2:20ish and other than the second one they were all right there. It was stupid hot to start but felt pretty nice by the end, and now I know there is a track much closer to home.
2 mile warm up, straight into 4x 400 on/400 off, 1 mile cool down.
8th overall, 1st in age group. Finally got that sub 20 min 5k!

Activity Name: SARR run plus some extra credit

Activity Description: 7 miles cutting down to just under marathon pace, two mile cool down. Took an off day yesterday but the legs are still feeling sluggish.
7 with SARR then 4 on my own.
There was a gas leak at the zoo entrance, so we had to move to a smaller hill down the road.  2.5 mile warmup, 12x hill repeats
9 @ goal marathon pace +30 sec/mi.  Humid, but felt comfortable the entire way.
Felt terrible for the first 5 miles but then the legs finally loosened up and it was a little better.
9 with 4 at half marathon pace. Goal was 6:50 for the faster miles but wasn’t getting there today after a tough run on Saturday. 7:08, 7:02, 6:58, 7:02. 18 weeks to Houston!

Activity Name: Battle of Cibilo Creek 5 mile race
Activity Description: 4th overall, 1st in age group.

6 easy, 8 at 7:30/mi, 2 easy. Plan called for 8 at 7:05 but I adjusted to 7:30 for the weather. 80% humidity so I was squishing in my shoes by mile 5.  The last few miles were tough, but overall felt pretty good throughout.
Not sure what was going on with the GPS track on this one...

3 miles warm up, 2x 2 miles at half marathon pace (2 minute recovery), 2 miles down. Tired legs coming in to this one and all of the water fountains in the park were turned off. 6:55 goal pace for the fast miles. Went :57, :59, :51, 59 which isn’t too bad all things considered.
Cooler weather and people to run with makes a huge difference!  Easy effort and felt like I could have kept going. 2 weeks in a row over 60 miles

My legs were a little beat up from my long run and I’ve been having trouble being consistent at this pace so I broke out new shoes and took this one to the track. 3 easy, straight into 5 at HMP (6:50), 1 easy.  Completed in 6:57, 6:54, 6:47, 6:51, 6:52.

A little more than 8 easy miles, then 10 miles @ 7:20. Couldn’t quite hold on to the pace for the last couple of miles, but overall I’m happy with the workout. 64 miles on the week and 5 weeks of marathon training in the books.

6 easy, 5 at half marathon pace, short jog cool down. Targeted 6:50 for the fast miles, but didn’t quite get there. Felt strong after an easy week last week, but had a tough time maintaining pace on the greenway.

This one was tough, coming at the end of two higher mileage weeks and being on my own for the whole thing. 66 miles this week after 69 last week, and judging by how difficult this felt I’ve probably reached the upper limit of what I can handle for mileage.
2.5 up, 6 x 800m intervals, 2 mile cool down.
Nice easy effort. I really only did this race so I could get the little turkey on my map.
2 mike warmup, 5x600 with 400 jog recovery. 1 mile cool down.  Target was 2:15 and was right around that for all of them.

Activity Name: Rock and Roll San Antonio Half Marathon 2019
Activity Description: 1:28:06 officially, a 3 minute PR. Really happy with it considering the additional hills they added this year.  7th in age group, 78th of 8290 overall
This was 18 total but forgot to restart my watch after tying my shoe.  My hamstring was not happy for the last couple of miles, but other then that felt great!
Manually entering the 1.4 for forgetting to start my watch
2x3 miles at marathon pace

After a huge PR to run 3:20 last year I started to think a BQ was actually a possibility.  A running-friendly work schedule this year let me really up my mileage, and despite some nagging injuries limiting the ability to do speedwork, I was hopeful I could pull it off.  Was a little concerned how much effort I was putting in at 7-8 miles, and the wind was pretty tough in the second half, but I was able to maintain pace and finish over 4 minutes under my BQ standard, which should hopefully be enough for Boston in 2021!
First run in over two months, and 15 pounds heavier, so it was not pleasant.  What used to be a warmup is now apparently a workout, so it’s a good thing there are no races anytime soon!
Cooler temps, less cyclist traffic, and people to run with. Best long run in a while!
Planned 3x 1 mile @ 7:00/1 mile off. Hit the first mile but nearly passed out afterwards. So at this point I can maintain exactly 1 mile at marathon pace.
So. Much. Humidity.
First run faster than easy pace in almost a month. 2 mile warmup, 3 miles moderate, 2 cool down. 7:30 goal pace, and wasn’t too tough.
2 mile warmup, 4 miles of 2 min hard/1 minute easy, 2 mile cool down. Legs felt good considering it’s my first workout in a while.

Didn’t feel great to start but sometimes those turn into great long runs. This was not one of those times. The whole thing was a struggle but the last three were especially brutal. Looking forward to some group runssion to have some company for these sweat-fests

Eased down to 3 miles at marathon pace. Would have liked them to be in the 6:55 range but 7:08ish was where I settled in. I definitely need to get on the track and get some speed in my legs, but I’m at least starting to feel like I’m ready for a marathon training cycle.
9 easy, picked it up for 6, then a 1 mile cool down. 55 miles on the week and still feeling strong!
Nice to have someone to run with again!
Struggled pretty hard in the second half when It started getting pretty warm, but managed to limp it in to the finish.
Felt great for the second half after a sluggish start. It was a nice down week, but back to the grind next week!
Track workout was canceled, so went to Valero. Started easy, cutting down to a couple miles just over marathon pace, one mile cool down. Lots of mud and bikes after the rain, but felt pretty strong.
First 10 with SARR, then back out for 6 on my own.
Wanted to get to 6:45 for the fast miles but I just didn’t have it today. Heart rate wasn’t bad, but I just couldn’t get the legs to turn over.
8 easy, 6 @ 7:15, 2 easy. Felt comfortable the whole way but lots of traffic for the last few miles
Woke up too late to make it to the group run downtown so I had to slog through this one on my own.  Longest run of this buildup and still feeling good!

Activity Name: Houston is canceled, so I need a new race
Activity Description: Not surprised, but not sure what to do for a goal race now that Houston is gone. Louisiana is the same weekend, but may still cancel. BCS is probably going to happen, but it’s mid December and my training was for a mid-January race. Any other options for a fast marathon that is likely to happen?
Planned on 16-18, but the weather was perfect and the greenway wasn’t crowded.
Slept in because I’m soft and didn’t want to run in the cold.  Struggled a little to maintain pace in the last 3-4 miles, but pretty happy with the effort overall.
Missed the lap button to start the 4th mile. 6:45 goal pace but only managed 6:50ish.

Activity Name: 2 x 1 mile, 2 x .5 mile, 2 x .25 mile

Activity Description: No turkey trots this year so I went after a couple of crowns.
Easy miles in steady rain. Planned on some marathon pace in the second half, but decided against it with soaked shoes and slippery conditions.
Easy start building up to marathon effort. Pretty happy with the pace after a big week.
Cold, windy, and slow.
manual entry for stopped watch

Forgot to start the watch so I need to add .81 miles. With Steven for the first 5.5, then in my own for a little tour of the south side. Felt terrible and couldn’t get loose for the first 7, but finally settled in and felt great for the last 10k. Biggest long run and mileage week of this build up. Now 7 weeks to sharpen up.

Activity Name: Added mileage for not starting my watch

Activity Description: 3 miles warmup, 5x600 at 5k pace with 300 rest, cool down to 9 miles. The winds made the paces inconsistent, and I missed a button press or two.  Not an all out effort by any means.
3 mile warmup, straight into 6 x 1k & 5k pace with 3:25 jog recovery, cool down to 10 total.
30 minute warmup, 5x600 with 2:00 rest, cool down back home. Moderate effort; just trying to stay smooth while turning the legs over a little
3 miles approaching marathon pace with an easy mile between. Felt smooth but the wind was pretty brutal.
2 up, 6 half mile intervals @ 5k pace with quarter mile jogs, cool down.
9 with 4 at tempo pace.
Planned on 8x400 but was running late so only got 6 in.  No pace target, just trying to focus on maintaining form while picking up the leg speed a little.
3rd overall. 1st Master
6 x 400m at half marathon pace with 400m jogs. Plus warm up/cool down for 6 miles total.

Nice to be racing again!  The rolling start times meant weaving through slower runners for the entire race, and those hills were no joke, so not quite as fast as I would have liked. I remembered the huge hill at mile 13 but forgot how tough miles 9-12 are on this course. Going to take it easy for a couple weeks, then the marathon buildup begins again!
1 minute moderate/2 minutes easy for miles 3-5.
2 up, 5 mile progression down to marathon pace, 1 down
I forgot to set up the workout on the watch so had to keep an eye on the watch and manually split. 3x 1.5 miles at half marathon pace with 3 minute recovery jogs.
Waited out the rain, but then got turned around a couple times where the greenway was flooded. Heavy legs and low energy, but got it done.
2 up, 10x 400 with 400 jog, cool down to 8 miles. Was shooting for 1:22s, but didn’t get close with the humidity and tired legs.
Should have been 7 miles. Watch glitched somewhere in there…
6x400 with 400 rest. Planned to to do 6x200 as well but the heat was brutal so I called it off. Maybe if I hadn’t spent 90 minutes trying to find a track that was open I would have been ok.

2 mile warmup, 16 x 400 with 75 seconds recovery jogs.  Walk recovery after rep 4, 8, and 12.  Cool down to 9 miles.  Goal was 1:30 for the reps, but was more focused on turnover and form since I've been over striding and dropping my cadence lately.
13 with Steven then back out for 5 more. Longest run since January.  Glad the sun stayed away because I was pretty wiped at the end.
Muddy trip around the blue loop for my first time out with BRC, and took a good fall in the water early on.  It’s nice having a group that meets so close by!
2 mile warm up, 3 x 10 minutes at tempo effort with 2 minute jog recovery, 1 mile cool down.
My knee is still a little off, but no pain so it’s getting close…
Knee feels ok but my fitness has definitely taken a hit
Planned 18 with 2x 4 miles at race pace, but that wasn’t in the cards. Good company though and still got a solid run in!
Snuck in a short workout to make up for cutting Saturday’s workout short. 2 up, 2x 2 miles at marathon pace, 2 down. Walk recovery between the intervals. Felt way smoother than Saturday.

So gross out there, so took the first 12 super conservative.  Swapped out for dry shoes and shorts and ran the last 9 at normal pace. I don’t usually like carrying water but it would have been ugly if I hadn’t today.
Warmup, 3/2/1 miles tempo with 3/2 minute jog recovery.
Went out early to beat the heat but I think it cooled off and got breezy once the sun came up. Felt pretty good the whole way, until the last mile when the stomach got a little rough.
Tempo-effort 5 miler. Felt pretty good coming off Saturday’s long run, and looking forward to an easier week. 5 weeks until Boston!
Planned progression run but I’m still feeling last weekend in my legs so took it easy. Saw a few familiar faces out there taking advantage of the low 70s temps
12 on my own then joined up with Steven for the last 6. Legs felt strong after a nice string of easy days and some cooler temps.

2 mile warmup, then 5 miles steady. 3 minute jog followed by 5x 1 mile with 2 minute jog. Cool down back to the car. 

Felt great on the 5 miles, but midway through the second mile repeat the legs just gave up. No turnover from there on but tried to at least keep the effort honest.

Same route as 2 weeks ago, but started at the opposite end so the second half would be uphill. Kept it to two quick water refill stops to keep it as honest as possible and still ran a solid negative split for the second half.
Hamstrings are a little sore so skipped the tempo miles on the schedule. I may slip them in later this week when it isn’t 85 degrees.

60 minutes progressing down to marathon pace
20 minutes marathon pace
3 minutes MP + 20 sec
5x alternating 3 minutes @ MP and 5k pace
Cool down to 17

Last big one before Boston and feeling ready!
Legs are a still a little heavy from Sunday, so this felt more difficult than it probably should have.

First Boston in the books and it was everything it was billed to be. While my race didn’t go well, the experience was awesome and I’ll definitely be back. 

Held back through the first 7 or 8 miles then settled into a good rhythm. Felt good through 18 or so and was on target for 3:05 but started getting stomach cramps and stopped taking water. Tried some water and 23 and it was coming back up the rest of the way so just jogged it in. Even though the last miles were pretty rough I really enjoyed it and can’t wait to give it another shot.
Nice easy run to finish off a recovery week. Back to the grind on Monday!

Supposed to be 7 but wasn't paying attention and went way past the turnaround point.  Then tried to take a shortcut on the way back but the trail was flooded.  Legs feel almost recovered, but will probably skip the speed this week and just see how my legs respond to getting the mileage back to the upper 50's.

Some light rain in the first half and felt alright, but once it stopped raining the humidity and heavy legs just killed me.  Probably tried to crank the mileage back up too fast after Boston, so I'll dial it back a little in the next week or so.
First 12 with George and Bryan (4@8, 4@7:45, 4@7:30) then 8 on my own without looking at the watch. Felt easy the whole way!

Activity Name: Easy power line run with BRC

Activity Description: Nursing a hamstring strain so cut this back a little. Was going to be 12 @ 7-flat but didn’t feel great pushing off so just tried to keep the HR higher than normal LR pace.
Should have taken one more easy day before this workout. Was aiming for 800s at 5k pace, but ended up around HM pace.
6 solo, 13 on the RnR Half course with SARR. Then 3 more for 22 total.  The course is roughly the same as two years ago, but they somehow added another half mile long hill in there.
Planned 12 with 7 at HM pace, but didn’t have the turnover to get the pace down that far.
Perfect weather for a new PR, and 3rd in AG.
2525 miles for the year!
A little colder than yesterday!  Hadn’t run out this way in a while. They built new bathrooms at JFK and there’s new trail going south from Southside Lions Park
Going to be a breezy one…

3:09:36 chip time. Felt like I had the potential for a small PR today but it wasn’t to be. Stomach issues forced me to make a few stops and skip some gels, then I just ran out of gas at 23 and shuffled it in. It’s been a while since I’ve taken some time off so going to shut it down for a while before Boston.

Moved tomorrow’s workout to today because I’d rather run in the rain instead of the cold.

2 miles warmup, 3 miles @ 6:45, 3x1 mile @ 6:30 with 1 minute recoveries.
Same route as last week but did the Eisenhower-to-Rim section twice to get more hills and mileage.  Pushed a little harder the second trip but nothing crazy.
7 with a 4 mile progression from 3 - 6.  Legs a little heavy but my form felt smooth throughout
50 minutes easy, 20 minute push, 5 minutes cool down.
2 miles @ 6:40, 1 at 6:30, 2 @ 6:40. 3 minute jog recovery.  Screwed up the laps somehow and the 1 mile was closer to .75
All the water fountains were turned off, but at least Garmin says I’m now 48% heat acclimated.
Alternating km’s 10 seconds under and 10 seconds over marathon pace.
2 mile warmup, 3 mile/2 mile/1 mile tempos with 3/2 minute jog recoveries. Felt kinda terrible throughout the whole thing…
2 mile warmup, 8x 3 minutes with 2 minutes rest.
6 miles tempo. Plan was to start out at 6:45s and work down to 6:30s, but I hit a wall along the way and slowed down to 7.
8x 1200m with 400m jog recoveries
Marathon pace workout. 2 weeks to Boston!
Just under 18 on the day

Activity Name: 3 miles @ MP, 2 x 1 mile at HMP
Activity Description: 90 second jog recoveries

So much fun out there and perfect weather!  I took it as easy as I could in the first half, high-fived kids and enjoyed the race. After halfway I tried to lock in a rhythm and get ready for the hills. Turns out a million trips between The Rim and Eisenhower was good prep cause I cruised through the Newton Hills without too much problem. The headwind picked up in the last 4 miles and I hit a pretty good wall at mile 24, but I managed to hold it together enough to stay under 3:07, which is only about 1:15 off my PR. 

I ran less total mileage this training cycle and just focused on the long runs and losing some weight. It helped me lose 15 lbs but most of my workouts were garbage.  Looking forward to hitting this training cycle hard and going for sub-3 at Chicago!
Threw in 3x 60 sec on/off pickups. Legs are still pretty heavy and sluggish, so probably another recovery week ahead.

2 miles warm up, 3 miles of 90 seconds on 30 seconds off, cool down. 

Was supposed to get faster as the workout progressed but had trouble gauging how hard to push since I haven’t had a workout in a few weeks.  Those 30 second recoveries seemed really quick, but still felt decent at the end of the workout.
It had been a while since I joined the Friday meet up.  Hopefully I can get more group runs in this summer!

6x 3 minutes on with 1 minute float. Progressively faster on the hard sections while trying to keep the floats slightly faster than easy pace. A little quick on the first rep but otherwise kept pretty close to the plan.

3 easy, 6 mile progression, 2 mile cool down. Goal was to work down to 6:40 pace, and didn’t quite make it, but happy with the effort. [strava://athletes/2019923/9]Guy Rubio sighting in the first mile, and lots of runners out putting in work!
2 easy, 6 x 1k with 75 second rest.  Goal was 4:05-4:10 per km, which I hit, but it was supposed to be much easier than it ended up feeling.
